Did you know that the calf muscle is actually made up of two muscles: gastrocnemius and soleus?🐮⁣
⁣
The gastrocnemius is the larger muscle, forming that massive bulge visible beneath the skin. It has two "heads", which together create its iconic diamond shape. The soleus is a smaller, flat muscle that lies underneath the gastrocnemius muscle.⁣
⁣
Together they taper and merge at the base of the calf muscle, helping us to run when we're being late to work or lectures.😂🏃‍♀️

Curious Monday: Breastfeeding Facts ❤⁣
⁣
It's World Breastfeeding Week, so I thought it would be fun to highlight some of the interesting facts related to this process and perhaps break the stigma surrounding it!💪 Let's go:⁣
⁣
- A mother's breasts can gain up to 2 pounds each in preparation for feeding an infant 🏋️‍♀️⁣
- In nearly 3/4 of new mothers, the right breast makes more milk than the left 👉⁣
- Breastfeeding creates more dense tissue in the breasts. After breastfeeding, both fatty tissue and connective tissue can shrink, change the size, or even make one breast seem larger than the other ⚖⁣
- Milk changes its nutritional profile as the baby grows (milk made for a 3-month-old is different than for a 9-month-old) ⏳⁣
- Breast milk is not always white. It can have shades of blue, green, pink, orange, or yellow (hence the nickname "liquid gold") depending on what the mother eats or drinks. It’s most often safe for the baby though!🎨⁣
⁣
Hope you've found this interesting guys!

🧠ANATOMY QUIZ🧠⁣ - Finished, thank you so much everyone for your insightful answers, well done!!🥳 This week's randomly selected winner was announced in a story 🧠 Answer is at the end of this caption 👇

node.text:
Ok, so I've got a quick question for you: did you know that you can potentially live with just one carotid artery? 😳⠀
⠀
The carotid arteries are major blood vessels in the neck that supply blood to the brain, neck, and face. There are two carotid arteries (one on the right and one on the left), and sometimes they can get narrowed because of a build-up of plaque. It is known as carotid artery disease. ⠀
⠀
So what happens when one of the arteries gets 100% blocked? Well, it's really bad indeed, but some people can function normally even with one blocked artery (provided they haven't had a disabling stroke), as there are other arteries supplying blood to the brain. ⠀
⠀
This means that some can manage to live with only one carotid artery by implementing lifestyle changes like quitting smoking, changing their diet, and getting more exercise. Our bodies are incredible!♥️

Curious Monday: What Is Pectus Excavatum?⁣
⁣
Pectus Excavatumbis a congenital condition in which a person's sternum is pressed inwards, and they have a dip between their ribs.⁣
⁣
Usually, the ribs and sternum go outward at the front of the chest. With pectus excavatum, the sternum goes inward to form a depression in the chest. This gives the chest a caved-in look, which is why the condition is also sometimes called funnel chest or sunken chest. While some people with funnel chests will live a normal life, severe cases of pectus excavatum can eventually interfere with the function of the heart and lungs. ⁣
⁣
Interestingly, it’s more common in boys, and about 1 in 300 children will have funnel chests.⁣
⁣
Have you heard of, or encountered, this condition before? 🤔
